In inorganic fluorescent probes, CDs as fluorescent chemsensor have attracted more and more attention among researchers to exploit their potential in bioimaging, molecular detection and photocatalysis in modern times due to their excellent fluorescence properties like optical stability and excitation-dependent emission, especially good biocompatibility and low cytotoxicity [21–23]. The surface of CDs contains carboxyl and amino functional groups, etc. The fluorescent probe with halogen (Cl, Br and I) is no fluorescence because the halogen moiety is also a well-known fluorescence quencher in light of its heavy atom effect [24,25]. The halogen moiety might be substituted by the –SH group, which elicits a significant fluorescence increase [26,27]. Keeping these in mind, we designed and synthesized CDs containing amino functional groups and then covalently linked to bromoacetyl bromide molecules to form bromoacetyl bromide-functionalized CDs (CDs-Br) fluorescent probe (Scheme 2
                     ) based on CDs’ excellent fluorescence properties and mechanism of organic fluorescent probes, the mechanism of this probe for the detection of GSH/Cys/Hcy is the halogen substitution cyclization and ICT process as shown in Scheme 1 
                     [18]. The results indicated that the halogen moiety based on probe was more specific toward GSH over Hcy/Cys in phosphate buffered saline (PBS) aqueous solution than most of aldehyde or acrylate-based fluorescent probes, thus creating opportunity for studying the GSH related physiological processes and diseases in biological systems. Moreover, this fluorescent probe that could discriminate them and it has also been successfully applied to monitoring GSH in living cells.
